      "id": 1,
      "text": "Russell Gardens began as a 135‑acre estate owned by Captain Frederick Russell before being transformed into a planned community.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Gardens%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Francis H. developed Russell Gardens from Captain Frederick Russell’s former estate, naming the new community after the original landowner.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3,
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Gardens%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Actor Fredric March and his wife Florence Eldridge once called Russell Gardens home.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        7,
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Gardens%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "There are no train stations inside Russell Gardens; the nearest Long Island Rail Road stops are Great Neck and Little Neck.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        9,
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Gardens%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Residents opposed being absorbed by neighboring Thomaston and instead incorporated Russell Gardens as its own village in 1931.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12,
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Gardens%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "In 1981, Russell Gardens opened its own Village Justice Court, allowing local handling of traffic and municipal code matters.",
